message.content:
The start symbol S can expand only in one of three ways:

1. S → NT22 NT81  
2. S → NT39 NT49  
3. S → NT81 NT42  

Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form, each of NT22, NT39, NT81, NT42 and NT49 must cover contiguous pieces of the final string.

Observations about the five non‑terminals:

• NT49 has only the terminal rule NT49 → 't14'.  
  → If production (2) were used, the last symbol of the string would have to be t14.

• NT42 has only the terminal rules NT42 → 't7' | 't1' | 't3' | 't10'.  
  → If production (3) were used, the last symbol of the string would have to be one of t7, t1, t3 or t10.

• NT81 is defined solely by NT81 → NT66 NT26.  
  NT26 in turn has only the terminal rule NT26 → 't9'.  
  Consequently, any substring generated by NT81 must end with the single terminal t9.

Hence:

• With S → NT39 NT49 the string would have to end in t14 (it ends in t15) – impossible.  
• With S → NT81 NT42 the string would have to end in a terminal that NT42 can produce (t7, t1, t3, t10) – impossible.  
• With S → NT22 NT81 the entire string would have to end in t9 (because the NT81 part must finish with NT26 → t9) – impossible, since the given string ends in t15.

Because all three possible first productions for S are incompatible with the last symbol t15 of the given string, there is no derivation of the string from the grammar.
